# Project Structure Standards

## Package Layout

- Follow Python package best practices with src/ layout
- Use pyproject.toml for modern Python packaging
- Maintain clear separation between source code and configuration
- Keep tests in separate directory structure
- Use requirements/ directory for dependency management

## Django App Structure

```
src/django_ergo/
├── __init__.py          # Package initialization
├── apps.py              # Django app configuration
├── models.py            # Data models
├── views.py             # View logic
├── urls.py              # URL routing
├── admin.py             # Django admin configuration
├── settings.py          # App-specific settings
├── utils.py             # Utility functions
├── mixins.py            # Reusable model/view mixins
├── migrations/          # Database migrations
├── static/              # Static files
└── templates/           # Django templates
```

## Configuration Files

- `pyproject.toml` - Primary project configuration
- `Makefile` - Development commands and automation
- `.pre-commit-config.yaml` - Code quality automation
- `requirements/` - Dependency management by environment
- `.editorconfig` - Editor consistency
- `conftest.py` - Test configuration

## Directory Organization

- `src/` - Source code (follows src layout pattern)
- `tests/` - Test files mirroring src structure
- `requirements/` - Environment-specific dependencies
- `.cursor/` - Cursor AI configuration and rules
- `docs/` - Documentation (when added)

## File Naming Conventions

- Use snake_case for Python files and directories
- Use descriptive names that indicate purpose
- Group related functionality in modules
- Use `__init__.py` for package/module initialization
- Prefix private modules with underscore when appropriate

## Import Organization

- Use absolute imports from package root
- Group imports: standard library, third-party, local
- Use `from django_ergo import ...` for internal imports
- Avoid circular imports through careful module design
- Use `__all__` to control public API

## Settings Architecture

- Use namespaced settings (DJANGO_ERGO)
- Provide sensible defaults in DEFAULTS dict
- Support string import notation for classes
- Document removed settings for migration guidance
- Use environment variables for deployment-specific config

## Migration Strategy

- Keep migrations focused and atomic
- Test migrations with realistic data
- Document complex migrations
- Use RunPython for data migrations when needed
- Maintain backward compatibility

## Static Files Organization

```
static/django_ergo/
├── css/
├── js/
├── images/
└── fonts/
```

## Template Organization

```
templates/django_ergo/
├── base.html
├── components/
└── pages/
```

## Example

<example>
# Good project structure additions
src/django_ergo/
├── ai/
│   ├── __init__.py
│   ├── models.py          # AI-specific models
│   ├── embeddings.py      # Embedding utilities
│   └── knowledge.py       # Knowledge management
├── api/
│   ├── __init__.py
│   ├── serializers.py     # DRF serializers
│   ├── views.py           # API views
│   └── urls.py            # API URLs
└── management/
    └── commands/
        ├── __init__.py
        └── import_knowledge.py  # Custom management command

# Good import structure
from __future__ import annotations

import uuid
from typing import Optional, List

from django.db import models
from django.contrib.auth import get_user_model

from django_ergo.mixins import TimeStampedMixin
from django_ergo.ai.embeddings import generate_embedding

User = get_user_model()
</example>

<example type="invalid">
